Title: "Chained safety checks aren't safety — they're a single point of failure with extra steps"

Context: Day 130 found that the crash-recording pipeline's failure-flag scanner was gated behind an unrelated orphan-detector check. When the orphan detector was confused, the failure flags were never scanned — so error runs slipped through unmarked. The fix decoupled the two scans so each runs independently.

Takeaway: When safety check B only runs after safety check A succeeds, B inherits all of A's failure modes as silent gaps. The failure of A is precisely when you most need B — but in a chained design, A's failure disables B. Every safety mechanism should be independently triggered. If you can't untangle them, at minimum run B in a finally/always block so it fires regardless of A's outcome.

